05344nam a22007815i 9780801461033DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979910337  a97808014610337 a10.7591/97808014610332doi  a(DE-B1597)478656  a(OCoLC)878694330  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHT221b.W65 2016 7aSOC0260302bisacsh04a307.33622231 aWoldoff, Rachael A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhite Flight/Black Flight :bThe Dynamics of Racial Change in an American Neighborhood /cRachael A. Woldoff. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b1 table, 2 charts/graphs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: What Happens to a Neighborhood after White Flight? -- t1. The Parkmont Environment -- t2. Choosing Parkmont: Whites Staying and Blacks Pioneering -- t3. Stella Zuk’s Story: Choosing to Stay -- t4. Cross-Racial Caregiving: Pioneers Helping Stayers to Age in Place -- t5. Ken Wilkinson: Striving for the Next Generation -- t6. Black Flight: Consequences of Neighborhood Cultural Conflict -- t7. Billy’s Narrative: Clashing in Parkmont -- t8. Skipping School: The Negative Effects of a Neighborhood Institution -- t9. Conclusions: Understanding the Cultural Dynamics of Neighborhood Change -- tAppendix -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUrban residential integration is often fleeting—a brief snapshot that belies a complex process of racial turnover in many U.S. cities. White Flight/Black Flight takes readers inside a neighborhood that has shifted rapidly and dramatically in race composition over the last two decades. The book presents a portrait of the life of a working-class neighborhood in the aftermath of white flight, illustrating cultural clashes that accompany racial change as well as common values that transcend race, from the perspectives of three different groups who are living it: white stayers, black pioneers, and "second-wave" blacks.Rachael A. Woldoff offers a fresh look at race and neighborhoods by documenting a two-stage process of neighborhood transition and focusing on the perspectives of two understudied groups: newly arriving black residents and whites who have stayed in the neighborhood. Woldoff describes the period of transition when white residents still remain, though in diminishing numbers, and a second, less discussed stage of racial change: black flight. She reveals what happens after white flight is complete: "Pioneer" blacks flee to other neighborhoods or else adjust to their new segregated residential environment by coping with the loss of relationships with their longer-term white neighbors, signs of community decline, and conflicts with the incoming second wave of black neighbors.Readers will find several surprising and compelling twists to the white flight story related to positive relations between elderly stayers and the striving pioneers, conflict among black residents, and differences in cultural understandings of what constitutes crime and disorder.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAfrican American neighborhoodszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aEthnic neighborhoodszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aResidential mobilityzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aSocial changezUnited StatesvCase studies. 4aDiscrimination & Race Relations. 4aU.S. History. 4aUrban Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 20